/PG230/XX/PR

Hallelu/Yah!/PR

Call out to Yah in Heavenòs holy place!/PR

Boom out to Yah across the firmament!/PR

Shout out for Yah, for all Godòs mighty deeds!/PR

Cry out for Yah, as loud as God is great!/PR

Blast out for Yah with piercing shofar note!/PR

Pluck out for Yah with lute and violin!/PR

Throb out for Yah with drum and writhing dance!/PR

Sing out for Yah with strings and husky flute!/PR

Ring out for Yah with cymbals that resound!/PR

Clang out for Yah with cymbals that rebound!/PR

Let every living thing Yahòs praises sing, Hallelu/Yah!/PR

Let every living thing Yahòs praises sing, Hallelu/Yah!/PR

Psalm 150/XX/PR

/PR

Blessed is /SCT/XXHE /XXO/XXNE/XX eternally./PR

Amen! Amen!/PR

Blessed is /SCT/XXHE /XXO/XXMNIPRESENT/XX,/PR

dwelling in Jerusalem, Halleluyah!/PR

Blessed is /SCT/XXHE /XXM/XXIGHTY /XXO/XXNE/XX divine,/PR

The God of Israel who alone works wonders,/PR

and blessed is the glorious name forever,/PR

and may Godòs glory fill the earth./PR

Amen! Amen!/PR

/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. Psalm 150 as it appears in the biblical text does not repeat
its concluding line as it does in the liturgy. The repetition here makes this
concluding verse parallel to all the preceding ones, allowing it to fit a vari-
ety of musical settings. The repetition also emphasizes the psalmòs essential
message.    /SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

