/PG232/XX/PR

/KAINTERPRETIVE NISHMAT KOL H/±AY/XX/PR

When the night slides under with the last dimming star/PR

and the red sky lightens between the trees,/PR

and the heron glides tipping heavy wings in the river,/PR

when crows stir and cry out their harsh joy,/PR

and swift creatures of the night run toward their burrows,/PR

and the deer raises her head and sniffs the freshening air,/PR

and the shadows grow more distinct and then shorten,/PR

/PR

then we rise into the day still clean as new snow./PR

The cat washes its paw and greets the day with gratitude./PR

Leviathan salutes breaching with a column of steam./PR

The hawk turning in the sky cries out a prayer like a knife./PR

We must wonder at the sky now thin as a speckled eggshell,/PR

that now piles up its boulders of storm to crash down,/PR

that now hangs a furry grey belly into the street./PR

/PR

Every day we find a new sky and a new earth/PR

with which we are trusted like a perfect toy./PR

We are given the salty river of our blood/PR

winding through us, to remember the sea and our/PR

kindred under the waves, the hot pulsing that knocks/PR

in our throats to consider our cousins in the grass/PR

and the trees, all bright scattered rivulets of life./PR

/PR

We are given the wind within us, the breath/PR

to shape into words that steal time, that touch/PR

like hands and pierce like bullets, that waken/PR

truth and deceit, sorrow and pity and joy,/PR

that waste precious air in complaints, in lies,/PR

in floating traps for power on the dirty air./PR

Yet holy breath still stretches our lungs to sing./PI/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PL233/XXNISHMAT KOL H/±AY/XX/PR

We are given the body, that momentary kibbutz/PR

of elements that have belonged to frog and polar/PR

bear, corn and oak tree, volcano and glacier./PR

We are lent for a time these minerals in water/PR

and a morning every day, a morning to wake up,/PR

rejoice and praise life in our spines, our throats,/PR

our knees, our genitals, our brains, our tongues./PR

/PR

We are given fire to see against the dark,/PR

to think, to read, to study how we are to live,/PR

to bank in ourselves against defeat and despair/PR

that cool and muddy our resolves, that make us forget/PR

what we saw we must do. We are given passion/PR

to rise like the sun in our minds with the new day/PR

and burn the debris of habit and greed and fear./PR

/PR

We stand in the midst of the burning world/PR

primed to burn with compassionate love and justice,/PR

to turn inward and find holy fire at the core,/PR

to turn outward and see the world that is all/PR

of one flesh with us, see under the trash, through/PR

the smog, the furry bee in the apple blossom,/PR

the trout leaping, the candles our ancestors lit for us./PR

/PR

Fill us as the tide rustles into the reeds in the marsh./PR

Fill us as the rushing water overflows the pitcher./PR

Fill us as light fills a room with its dancing./PR

Let the little quarrels of the bones and the snarling/PR

of the lesser appetites and the whining of the ego cease./PR

Let silence still us so you may show us your shining/PR

and we can out of that stillness rise and praise./PR

Marge Piercy/XX/PR

